  "prompt": "Why do airplanes use two-pronged headphones?",
  "response": "Airplanes often use two-pronged headphone jacks for several reasons:\n\n1. **Compatibility and Control**: The two-pronged system allows airlines to manage the audio and microphone separately. It separates the channels, giving more control over the in-flight entertainment system and ensuring compatibility with the aircraft\u2019s audio configuration.\n\n2. **Historical Reasons**: This setup originates from older systems that required separate connections due to technological limitations at the time. While technology has advanced, many airlines have continued using the system for consistency and to maintain compatibility with existing hardware.\n\n3. **Deterrence Against Theft**: Using a non-standard headphone jack can deter passengers from taking the headphones with them, as these headphones are less likely to be compatible with personal devices outside the plane.\n\n4. **Cost Considerations**: Airlines often provide complimentary or low-cost headphones for passengers, and sticking to an older or proprietary standard can be more cost-effective than upgrading to universal jacks fleet-wide.\n\nWhile some modern aircraft are shifting towards more common single jack systems, the two-pronged system remains prevalent in many airlines due to these reasons.",
